      <td width="94" valign="top"><img src="../../../images/robbery/fly%20money.GIF" width="102" height="80" align="top"></td>
      <td width="534"><p align="center" class="style8">Employee Theft</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">Managers can reduce internal theft by 60% simply by letting employees know that management is watching. With so much money at stake, why don't all managers face the issue head on? The answer is theft control is time consuming and no one likes playing cop. Also, many managers hate to admit they're being taken, or just can't fathom that a member of their team is stealing from them. </p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">Spotting theft isn't necessarily difficult -- it just takes diligence. A variance of more than half a % on food cost should be considered odd enough to check out. An unusual food cost variance can mean food is going out the door or someone has figured out a way to turn food into money by manipulating the POS system, otherwise known as embezzlement. </p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">Employees steal in various ways, theft of cash, product and time. Let's take a closer look at each:</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4"><strong>Cash Shortages -</strong> This can be caused by procedure errors, so, before assuming an employee is consciously stealing money, ensure that they have been properly trained and follow Shari's cash handling procedures. This, by the way, is an easy fix. Train and monitor employees while working the floor. </p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">Inform all employees on the shift of the shortage, sometimes knowing that the management team is aware and watching can curb a thief. Post the Cash Over Short report ran out of RAS, highlight shortages for all to see.</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">If an employee is cashing checks out in their station this could indicate that the cash left by the guest may not be making it up front and in the till. Run the Work Station Closed Check report in POS and discipline the employee for closing a cash check in their station.</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">Review video, if available, look for employees taking money out of the till and placing it directly in their pocket. If you see this on the tape, ask the employee why they did this, document, train and possibly discipline appropriately.</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">Locking down the till may solve a cash shortage problem on a shift, but will never solve a cash shortage problem permanently or catch a thief. Locked down tills impede guest service and quite frankly angers your crew. If you listen carefully you may hear an employee tell a guest &quot;I'd help you, but, I'm not allowed in the register&quot; or something similar. Our guests shouldn't have to wait to pay their bill because we have a thief working for us. Locked down tills will not catch or stop a thief from stealing, they will just steal something else, perhaps another server's tips or products.</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4"><strong>Theft of Product -</strong> One of the most common forms of stealing products, is grazing. Keep a close eye on employee meal tickets, did you see an employee eating on break without a employee meal ticket? Are the servers munching on brownie chunks, cucumber slices or cups of soup? When you spot someone not following policy, bring it to their attention immediately and correct the given situation.</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">Discourage employees from bringing large bags into the restaurant, and never let them keep them in food storage areas. We do realize that some of our cook staff carry bags containing their personal egg pans, knives, spats etc. to work each day. Always involve your District Manager in decisions to search an employee's personal property.</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">Giving away food or drinks to friends. Make sure everyone is aware that the only person authorized to give away food is the manager on duty. Track walk-outs by server, speak to the server involved to find out how it happened. Walk-outs can be food given away or cash stolen. Document and discipline appropriately.</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">Oversee trash disposal. Conduct periodic trash audits. Designate one person to take trash out and have a manager accompany the employee.</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">To keep temptation at bay, adjust food pars regularly. The less inventory on hand, the less there is to steal.</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4"><strong>Theft of Time -</strong> Often employees don't realize that they are in fact stealing time from you. Taking unauthorized breaks, personal phone calls, visiting with co-workers instead of completing side work in a timely fashion are just a few examples of time lost or stolen. This type of theft is easily managed, awareness is key, when confronted with a group of employees visiting simply break the group up by giving each of them a task to complete. </p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">When excusing an employee from their work area at the end of the shift ask them if their side work is complete. If they say yes, check it, thank them for a job well done and say &quot;see you tomorrow&quot;. If their answer is no, ask them to complete it and let them know that you will be back shortly to check them out. Never allow the employee to take a &quot;break&quot; and then return to complete their duties. These &quot;breaks&quot; can represent 15 or more minutes of lost labor.</p>
      <p align="left"><strong>Preventing Employee Theft:</strong></p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">One of the worst mistakes managers make is failing to establish an in-store theft policy that lets employees know that theft is not tolerated. Unless a policy is in place, employees charged with theft can claim ignorance.</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">For new employees, clarify polices regarding:</p>
      <ul>
        <li class="style4">
          <div align="left" class="style4">Eating and drinking on the job.</div>
        </li>
                  <li class="style4"></li>
                  <div align="left" class="style4">Cash register procedures for voids, discounts, no-sales, and shift end reports.</div>
          <li class="style4">
            <div align="left"><span class="style4">Giving away food and drinks to friends.
</span></div>
          </li>
          <li class="style4">
            <div align="left" class="style4">
              <div align="left">Inventory, delivery and invoice procedures.</div>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="style4">
            <div align="left" class="style4">Garbage disposal--designate who is to do it, when and accompanied by whom.</div>
          </li>
          <li class="style4">
            <div align="left" class="style4">Employee entry and exit.</div>
          </li>
          <li class="style4">
            <div align="left" class="style4">Personal property, what employees can and cannot bring to work. </div>
          </li>
      </ul>      
      <p align="left" class="style4">For minor offenses, set up a warning system. If employees fail to follow policy repeatedly, replace them. Following through on your word shows you mean business. Failing to follow through invites others to ignore policies. </p>      </td>
    </tr>
