      <td width="525"><p align="center" class="style8">Customer Theft</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">A very small percentage of our guests are truly out to rip us off. As stated earlier, not everyone is honest, and customer theft does indeed happen.</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4"><strong>Quick Change Artists -</strong>The most crafty of these thieves are the quick change artists. Often the person dealing with this customer has the feeling something isn't &quot;quite right&quot;. Train your staff to use the following tips to foil the thief's plan.</p>
      <div align="left">
        <ul>
            <li class="style4">
              <span class="style4">Handle one transaction at a time. </span></li>
            <li class="style4">Always count back change, twice, first in your head and then aloud to the guest. </li>
            <li class="style4">If the guest asks for change for a twenty, lay the bill on the counter, gather the change from the till, count it back to them, when the guest is satisfied, place the twenty in the drawer and close the till.</li>
            <li class="style4">Don't let the guest interrupt you by asking to exchange other bills with the twenty out and the till still open. Finish the first transaction, close the till, and re-open the till to complete another request. </li>
            <li class="style4">Quick change artists have set routines, they know to confuse the cashier and walk off with their original twenty plus more. Separating each transaction foils their slight of hand routine. </li>
          </ul>
        <p class="style4"><strong>Guests That Walk-Out Without Paying - </strong>For your safety <em>NEVER</em> run outside to collect money from a guest that walks-out without paying. If you can get a license plate number by looking out the window, great. But leaving the building can be dangerous. Desperate people use desperate measures to escape. Check the open tables in POS looking for red tickets, ensure that your servers are delivering the guest check to the table when they deliver the food. Keeping the servers in their stations benefits your business in many ways such as: better guest service, higher sales and less walk-outs. Some guests walk out because they get tired of waiting at the register to pay. If you are appropriately staffed and your server is doing their job, the guest should never have to wait. Always speak with the server who had the walk-out. Ask them how it happened. Let them know that being too busy is never a good excuse, encourage them to ask for help before they get deep in the weeds. If a guest who has dined and dashed returns to your restaurant, inform your staff to notify you immediately. Be sensitive when approaching the guest to ask for payment. I like to give them the benefit of the doubt or the easy way out by saying something like, &quot;I'm sure this was an oversight, but the other day when you had lunch the check wasn't paid, would you like to take care of that this visit?&quot; As with any other sticky situation, keep in mind that other guests are probably listening to you so try to be as pleasant and discreet as possible. </p>
        <p class="style4"><strong>Counterfeit Cash -</strong> It is a good idea for managers to handle transactions that involve a $100.00 bill. Train your crew to check money for obvious counterfeit bills or to ask for help whenever unsure of authenticity.</p>
        <ul class="style4">
          <li><span class="style4">Hold the bill up to the light and look for the security thread. </span></li>
          <li><span class="style4">Check the two serial numbers to ensure that they match. </span></li>
          <li><span class="style4">Look for the water mark located to the right front side of the bill. The watermark should be visible from both sides when held up to light.</span></li>
          <li><span class="style4">Check for color-shifting ink. Color-shifting ink changes color when viewed from different angles. This ink is used to print the number in the lower right-hand corner on the front of the bill. The ink looks green when viewed straight on, but changes to black when the paper is held at an angle. </span></li>
          <li><span class="style4">Look for the obvious, ink that smudges or paper that feels too smooth. Paper used for US currency contains tiny blue and red threads that are embedded in the paper.</span></li>
          </ul>
        <p><span class="style4">There are many products on the market to help identify counterfeit currency such as marking pens and pen lights. These products are good and used frequently however, the counterfeiters of today are crafty so no system is fool proof. Should you encounter a bill that you think may be counterfeit, keep in mind the guest who is trying to spend it probably isn't the thief that manufactured it. Mention your concern to the guest and ask if they have another form of payment. You may even suggest that they take the bill to their local bank to check it for authenticity.</span></p>
        <p><span class="style4"><strong>Guests Getting Something For Nothing -</strong> A very small percentage of our guests come in with the plan to get something for free. They are out there, but the damage we do when arguing with the guest is much more detrimental to your business than &quot;letting them get one over on you.&quot; Some examples of this are:</span></p>
        <ul class="style4">
          <li><span class="style4">The guest who brings in their own bug to place in their salad after eating 3/4 of it. This guest will complain and usually inform you that they shouldn't be charged for their meal. Apologize, offer to replace the salad, do what you need to do and please the guest. Remember, your other guests are listening.</span></li>
          <li><span class="style4">The guest that sneaks the contents of the sugar caddy, condiment bottles or jelly basket into their bag. Refill the sugar caddy, ignore the missing bottle of ketchup or jelly basket and move on with your day. It's just not worth the time and energy to fight it out.</span></li>
          </ul>
        <p align="center"><strong><em>Remember, whenever you argue with a guest you may win the battle, but in fact lose the war. It's just not worth it!</em></strong></p>
        <p class="style4"><strong>Guests Who Steal Tips -</strong> The last thing we would want to do is accuse the guest of stealing. The solution to this problem is for your servers to buss their tables immediately when the table is empty. Another solution is for the servers to be visible in their stations and attentive to their guests which in turn should raise tip income. </p>
      </div>      
      <ul>
      </ul></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td valign="top"><img src="../../../images/robbery/fly%20money.GIF" width="102" height="80" align="top"></td>
      <td><p align="center" class="style8">Purveyor Theft </p>
      <p align="left" class="style4">Purveyor theft is the easiest to control. Having solid systems and following those systems every delivery can eliminate purveyor theft. </p>
      <p align="left" class="style4"><strong>Delivery Errors - </strong>Check in products carefully. Weigh-it, count-it, check-it! Match products and the amount directly to the invoice. Never take the word of the delivery person, check for yourself. If a product is listed on your invoice but not present, point it out to the driver and obtain a credit. Watch the pricing on invoices, incorrect pricing may not be blatant theft, but being over charged affects your bottom line. It is best not to accept deliveries at peak meal periods, managers often feel rushed and mistakes are easily made.</p>
      <p align="left" class="style4"><strong>Taking products -</strong> Keep your back door locked. Stay with the driver as they deliver their goods and inspect boxes or products when they are removed from your restaurant. Some purveyors have been known to &quot;graze&quot; on products while talking with crew members. Let it be known to both your staff and the driver that this is unacceptable. Should you have a serious problem with a particular driver or vendor, notify your district manager immediately.</p>
      <p align="center" class="style5">Remember To Inspect What You Expect! </p>
      <p align="center" class="style5">It's Not Often That We Get To Be The Customer!</p>      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
